'''Alyse Cynthia Eady''' (born March 15, 1988) is an American news anchor and beauty pageant titleholder who was [[Miss Arkansas]] 2010. Eady was named first runner-up at the [[Miss America 2011|2011 Miss America]] pageant, which was won by [[Miss Nebraska]] 2010 [[Teresa Scanlan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missamerica.org/news/press-releases.aspx?id=480|title=2011 Miss America Pageant Returns to Planet Hollywood in Las Vegas!|last2=|first2=|date=July 22, 2010|publisher=Miss America Organization|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120503071601/http://missamerica.org/news/press-releases.aspx?id=480|archive-date=3 May 2012|last1=|first1=|work=|accessdate=July 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/profile/Anup%20Mehra/clipnumber/121365/|title=Miss Arkansas 'Stuck in Dallas' By Winter Storm|last=|first=|date=3 February 2011|work=Paris News|access-date=14 November 2016|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>

==Biography==
Eady is from [[Fort Smith, Arkansas]], and was a caretaker for both of her parents, who were ill when she was growing up.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1374561.html|title=Alyse Eady, Who Grew Up in Fo...|last=|first=|date=26 September 2006|work=The Washington Post|subscription=yes|access-date=14 November 2016|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> Eady's father became [[Visual impairment|blind]] and her mother had [[Systemic lupus erythematosus|lupus]] and had multiple surgeries when Eady was younger.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-11508B711FDB5988.html|title=Five Teens Gain Recognition, Reward|last=Strauss|first=Valerie|date=8 October 2006|work=Post-Tribune|subscription=yes|access-date=14 November 2016|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> Eady helped out by learning to cook, and assisting her mother to bathe and dress.<ref name=":1" /> During high school, she worked as a tutor for the local [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys and Girls Club]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-653179371.html|title=Remarks at Butterfield Junior High School in Van Buren, Arkanasas|last=Bush|first=George W.|date=17 May 2004|work=Weekly Compilation of Presidential Documents|subscription=yes|access-date=14 November 2016|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref>

Eady graduated from [[Ouachita Baptist University]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[Mass Communications]] and [[Speech Communication]]. 

In 2004, she won the title of Miss Teen Arkansas-America 2004, which is now known as [[Miss America's Outstanding Teen state pageants#Arkansas|Miss Arkansas' Outstanding Teen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missarkansas.org/maot/maot_history.htm|title=MAOT History|last2=|first2=|date=|publisher=Miss Arkansas Organization|last1=|first1=|work=|accessdate=July 26, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100707064427/http://www.missarkansas.org/maot/maot_history.htm|archivedate=7 July 2010 <!--DASHBot-->|deadurl=no}}</ref> She performed in the Variety Act as a special guest during one of the Preliminary Competitions at [[Miss America 2007]] including her [[yodeling]] abilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vN3yyY09r30|title=The Clog Dancing Ventriloquist Beauty Queen|last2=|first2=|date=|publisher=YouTube|last1=Chiberoshka|first1=|work=|accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref> In 2010, she competed at [[Miss Arkansas]] as Miss South Central [[Arkansas]] and also won a Preliminary Talent Award and the Coleman Overall Talent Award at the pageant.  Her platform was the [[Boys and Girls Club of America]] and her talent is a Variety Act, in which she both sings and does [[ventriloquism]] to the song "[[I Want to Be a Cowboy's Sweetheart]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missarkansas.org/about_alyse.htm|title=About Alyse|last2=|first2=|date=|publisher=Miss Arkansas Organization|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110220192359/http://www.missarkansas.org/about_alyse.htm|archive-date=20 February 2011|last1=|first1=|work=|accessdate=July 26, 2010}}</ref>  Her act, which also included yodeling, was called "daring and skillful" by ''[[The Washington Post]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-27718909.html|title=Dole Out of Hospital Lennon Collector Sued Young Miss America|last=Melendez Olivera|first=Gabriela|date=17 January 2011|work=The Washington Post|subscription=yes|access-date=14 November 2016|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> 

At the [[Miss America 2011|Miss America]] pageant in 2011, Eady was named the first runner-up<ref name=":0" /> and won $25,000 in scholarships.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-27740428.html|title=Brown Makes Top Five at Miss America|last=Bowder|first=Mark|date=16 January 2011|work=The Columbian|subscription=yes|access-date=14 November 2016|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> In 2011, she also appeared on the ''Late Night Show With David Letterman''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1N1-134E82A91E086E48.html|title=The Oprah Winfrey Show (9a.m., Channel 7): Actor Russell|last=|first=|date=20 January 2011|work=Chicago Sun-Times|access-date=14 November 2016|via=}}</ref>

In 2013, Eady married her college sweetheart, Patrick Lemmond, on December 7, 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.arkansasbride.com/blog/post/99340/real-little-rock-wedding-alyse-eady-and-patrick-lemmond|title=Real Little Rock Wedding: Alyse and Patrick Lemmond|last=|first=|date=|work=Arkansas Bride|access-date=14 November 2016|via=}}</ref>

Eady previously worked as a news anchor for [[TEGNA]]-owned [[KTHV|KTHV-TV]], the local [[CBS]]-affiliated television station in [[Little Rock, Arkansas]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thv11.com/news/article/163144/139/Alyse-Eady/|title=Alyse Eady|last=|first=|date=9 October 2013|work=THV 11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228202942/http://www.thv11.com/news/article/163144/139/Alyse-Eady|archive-date=28 February 2014|access-date=14 November 2016|via=}}</ref> In August 2016, Eady joined [[WAGA-TV]] in [[Atlanta, GA]] as a morning news anchor.<ref>{{cite web|title=FOX 5 welcomes Alyse Eady to Good Day Atlanta|url=http://www.fox5atlanta.com/good-day/178144185-story|website=Fox5Atlanta.com|publisher=WAGA-TV|accessdate=2016-07-28}}</ref>

